{"parse":{"title":"Mention My Name in Atlantis","pageid":25381398,"revid":840741238,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><table class=\"infobox vcard\" style=\"width:22em\"><caption style=\"font-style:italic;padding-bottom:0.2em;\">Mention My Name in Atlantis <span class=\"Z3988\" title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Mention+My+Name+in+Atlantis&amp;rft.author=%5B%5BJohn+Jakes%5D%5D&amp;rft.date=1972&amp;rft.pub=%5B%5BDAW+Books%5D%5D\"></span></caption><tbody><tr><td colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\">\n<a href=\"/wiki/File:Mention_My_Name_in_Atlantis.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"Mention My Name in Atlantis.jpg\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/1/11/Mention_My_Name_in_Atlantis.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"336\" data-file-width=\"200\" data-file-height=\"336\" /></a><div>Cover of first edition</div></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Author</th><td>\n<a href=\"/wiki/John_Jakes\" title=\"John Jakes\">John Jakes</a></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Cover&#160;artist</th><td>\n<a href=\"/w/index.php?title=H._J._Bruck&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" class=\"new\" title=\"H. J. Bruck (page does not exist)\">H. J. Bruck</a></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Country</th><td>\nUnited States</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Language</th><td>\nEnglish</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Genre</th><td>\n<a href=\"/wiki/Fantasy\" title=\"Fantasy\">Fantasy</a></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Publisher</th><td>\n<a href=\"/wiki/DAW_Books\" title=\"DAW Books\">DAW Books</a></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\"><div style=\"padding:0.1em 0;line-height:1.2em;\">Publication date</div></th><td>\n1972</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Media&#160;type</th><td>\nPrint (<a href=\"/wiki/Paperback\" title=\"Paperback\">Paperback</a>)</td></tr></tbody></table>\n<p><i><b>Mention My Name in Atlantis, being, at last, the true account of the calamitous destruction of the great island kingdom together with a narrative of its wondrous intercourses with a superior race of other-worldlings, as transcribed from the manuscript of a survivor, Hoptor the Vintner, for the enlightenment of a dubious posterity</b></i> is a humorous <a href=\"/wiki/Fantasy\" title=\"Fantasy\">fantasy</a> novel written by <a href=\"/wiki/John_Jakes\" title=\"John Jakes\">John Jakes</a> purporting to give the \"true\" history of the sinking of the lost continent of <a href=\"/wiki/Atlantis\" title=\"Atlantis\">Atlantis</a>. It was first published in paperback by <a href=\"/wiki/DAW_Books\" title=\"DAW Books\">DAW Books</a> in October 1972, and reprinted by the same publisher in September 1975 and August 1976; the later printings featured new cover art by <a href=\"/wiki/Michael_Whelan\" title=\"Michael Whelan\">Michael Whelan</a>. A new paperback edition with an added introduction by the author was published by Bart Books in January 1988, and an ebook edition was issued by Open Road Integrated Media in December 2014. The book has also been translated into <a href=\"/wiki/German_language\" title=\"German language\">German</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Italian_language\" title=\"Italian language\">Italian</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Plot\">Plot</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Mention_My_Name_in_Atlantis&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Plot\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The story is told by the <a href=\"/wiki/Unreliable_narrator\" title=\"Unreliable narrator\">unreliable narrator</a> Hoptor the Vintner, a fast-talking operator with all the right contacts who is convinced in the face of mounting evidence to the contrary that he can smooth over anything. \"Mention my name\" is his tagline, meant to assure his auditors that dropping it in various quarters is their ticket to getting whatever they want. The book combines a number of cliches of the literature and pseudoscience regarding Atlantis, such as extraterrestrial visitors, as well as of the fantasy genre in general, most notably the ambitious barbarian brute, Conax of Chimeria, a satire on <a href=\"/wiki/Robert_E._Howard\" title=\"Robert E. Howard\">Robert E. Howard</a>'s <a href=\"/wiki/Sword_and_sorcery\" title=\"Sword and sorcery\">sword and sorcery</a> hero <a href=\"/wiki/Conan_the_Barbarian\" title=\"Conan the Barbarian\">Conan of Cimmeria</a>.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Reception\">Reception</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Mention_My_Name_in_Atlantis&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Reception\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p><a href=\"/wiki/Lester_del_Rey\" title=\"Lester del Rey\">Lester del Rey</a> described the satire as \"good-natured and sometimes amusing,\" but felt the idea of writing a humorous sword-and-sorcery novel was misconceived.<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Mention_My_Name_in_Atlantis&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.isfdb.org/cgi-bin/title.cgi?17372\"><i>Mention My Name in Atlantis</i></a> title listing at the <a href=\"/wiki/Internet_Speculative_Fiction_Database\" title=\"Internet Speculative Fiction Database\">Internet Speculative Fiction Database</a></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">\"Reading Room\", <a href=\"/wiki/If_(magazine)\" title=\"If (magazine)\"><i>If</i></a>, June 1973, pp.171-72</span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n<div role=\"navigation\" class=\"navbox\" aria-labelledby=\"Works_by_John_Jakes\" style=\"padding:3px\"><table class=\"nowraplinks collapsible autocollapse navbox-inner\" style=\"border-spacing:0;background:transparent;color:inherit\"><tbody><tr><th scope=\"col\" class=\"navbox-title\" colspan=\"2\"><div class=\"plainlinks hlist navbar mini\"><ul><li class=\"nv-view\"><a href=\"/wiki/Template:John_Jakes\" title=\"Template:John Jakes\"><abbr title=\"View this template\" style=\";;background:none transparent;border:none;-moz-box-shadow:none;-webkit-box-shadow:none;box-shadow:none; padding:0;\">v</abbr></a></li><li class=\"nv-talk\"><a href=\"/wiki/Template_talk:John_Jakes\" title=\"Template talk:John Jakes\"><abbr title=\"Discuss this template\" style=\";;background:none transparent;border:none;-moz-box-shadow:none;-webkit-box-shadow:none;box-shadow:none; padding:0;\">t</abbr></a></li><li class=\"nv-edit\"><a class=\"external text\" href=\"//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Template:John_Jakes&amp;action=edit\"><abbr title=\"Edit this template\" style=\";;background:none transparent;border:none;-moz-box-shadow:none;-webkit-box-shadow:none;box-shadow:none; padding:0;\">e</abbr></a></li></ul></div><div id=\"Works_by_John_Jakes\" style=\"font-size:114%;margin:0 4em\">Works by <a href=\"/wiki/John_Jakes\" title=\"John Jakes\">John Jakes</a></div></th></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\" class=\"navbox-group\" style=\"width:1%\">Brak the Barbarian</th><td class=\"navbox-list navbox-odd hlist\" style=\"text-align:left;border-left-width:2px;border-left-style:solid;width:100%;padding:0px\"><di